Given the function $f(x)=a- \frac{1}{x}-\ln x$, where $a$ is a constant.
(I) If $f(x)=0$ has exactly one solution, find the value of $a$;
(II) (i) If the function $g(x)=a- \frac{1}{x}- \frac{2(x-p)}{x+p}-f(x)-\ln p$, where $p$ is a constant, determine the monotonicity of the function $g(x)$;
(ii) If $f(x)$ has exactly two zeros $x_{1}$, $x_{2}(x_{1} < x_{2})$, prove that $x_{1}+x_{2} < 3e^{a-1}-1$.

